  "why": "The paper provides substantive, empirical diagnostic insight tied to model internals and statistical failure patterns, but it stops short of full root-cause attribution to underlying vulnerabilities (e.g., identifying specific spurious features or systematic dataset bias per failure). Concretely, DeepXplore introduces and measures neuron coverage (a model-internal coverage metric) and uses neuron activation analyses and class-level activation overlap to explain how tests exercise different parts of a model. The paper also demonstrates practical diagnostics: using generated failures to (a) detect polluted training data (95.6% detection) and (b) improve accuracy by retraining on generated inputs (up to 3%). These are clear, empirical links between observed failures and model internals / training-data issues, which qualifies as partial diagnostic analysis. However, the paper does not present detailed per-failure causal analyses that attribute failures to specific non-robust/spurious features or quantify dataset bias across output classes, so it does not meet the bar for “High.”",
